Back in the 2000s, the L.A. Times columnist Patrick Goldstein used to gathe=
r a group of high school kids, show them that summer=E2=80=99s big movie tr=
ailers, record their feedback, and present the insights of his =E2=80=9Csum=
mer movie posse=E2=80=9D as a kind of public focus group=E2=80=94a check-in=
 on how the studios were doing with the youth market. It was always fascina=
ting to see what the target audience was actually thinking about the produc=
t. The kids often rejected =E2=80=9Csurefire=E2=80=9D marketing strategies =
and cared more about stars that weren=E2=80=99t getting top billing.

Of course, today=E2=80=99s kids are far savvier about marketing and see tra=
ilers constantly on YouTube and social media, where they spend way more tim=
e than at the cineplex. But as we hit the heart of the summer, I wanted the=
 youth vote=E2=80=99s thoughts on the state of the major
theatrical franchises like Marvel, DC, and horror=E2=80=94and to hear about=
